				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} NPV = \sum _{t=1}^{n} \frac{R_{t}}{(1+RDR)^t}- I_0 \end{aligned}$$\end{document}If the NPV is positive, this means that the project is economically viable, covering the initial investment and generating a profit rate. In case the NPV is zero, it means the complete recovery of the initial investment. In this situation, the project’s viability is uncertain. If the NPV is negative, it means that the project is clearly not viable [2].

The Payback Period (PP) is the times it takes to recover the cost of an investment and can be computed through Eq. 4, where A is the last year with a negative cumulative cash flow, B is the absolute value of cumulative cash inflow at the end of year A, and C is the total cash flow during the year A+1. The smaller the PP, the better for the investor.4PP=A+BC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} PP = A+\frac{B}{C} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}

